You need two pieces: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and a **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with cancel logic and dirty-tracking

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "Discard changes and go back?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard)
                return;
        }

        HasUnsavedChanges = false;
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the system back button / swipe in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles *your* button, but users can also swipe back or use the hardware back button. Guard that in `OnNavigating` using `GetDeferral()`:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back-navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page's BindingContext is the edit VM
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage?.BindingContext
            is EditProductViewModel vm && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay" — cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete(); // always call this
    }
}
```

### How it all fits together

| Trigger | Handled by |
|---|---|
| User taps **Cancel** button | `BackButtonBehavior.Command` → `CancelCommand` |
| System back (swipe / hardware) | `AppShell.OnNavigating` guard |

**Key points:**
- Always call `GetDeferral()` before any `await` in `OnNavigating`, then `deferral.Complete()` after — otherwise the navigation completes before your dialog finishes.
- Set `HasUnsavedChanges = false` before `GoToAsync("..")` in `CancelCommand` so the `OnNavigating` guard doesn't double-prompt.
